miscontrue\/\/interpret in the wrong way\/\/con lau moi dung,hieu sai\/\/The politician never trusted journalists because he thought that they miscontrue his words and misrepresent his positions.
craven\/\/pathetically cowardly\/\/ra vuon\/\/Though the man could have at least alerted the police, he crouched cravenly in the corner as the old woman was mugged.
capricious\/\/determined by chance or impulse or whim rather than by necessity or reason\/\/cha co ri chuan\/\/Nearly every month our capricious CEO had a new plan to turn the company around, and none of them worked because we never gave them the time they needed to succeed.
ignominious\/\/(Used of conduct or character) deserving or bringing disgrace or shame.\/\/nhuc me no\/\/Since the politician preached ethics and morality, his texting of revealing photographs was ignominious bringing shame on both himself and his party
dilatory\/\/wasting time\/\/delay\/\/Lawyers use dilatory tactics so that it takes years before the case is actually decided.
maladroit\/\/clumsy\/\/may la droid, vung ve\/\/As a child, she was quite maladroid, but as an adult, she has become an adept dancer
deleterious\/\/harmful to living things\/\/delete\/\/The BP oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico was deleterious to the fishing insdustry in the southern states.
indecorous\/\/not in keeping with accepted standards of what is right or proper in polite society\/\/not decorous\/\/Eating with elbows on the table is considered indecorous in refined circles.
duress\/\/compulsory force or threat\/\/diu re, cau thuc, cuong ep, cuong che\/\/The witness said he signed the contract under duress and argued that the court should concel the agreement.
rebuke\/\/criticize severely or angrily; censure\/\/rat buc\/\/The police chief rebuked the two officers whose irresponsible decisions almost led to the deaths of seven innocent by-standers.
anomaly\/\/something that is not normal, standard or expected\/\/anomalous\/\/After finding an anomaly in the data, she knew that she would have to conduct her experiment again.
appease\/\/pacify by acceding to the demands of\/\/o peace\/\/Neville Chamberlain, the British prime minister during WWII, tried to appease Hitler and in doing so sent a clear message: you can walk all over us.
sullen\/\/showing a broading ill humor\/\/sung len, buon rau, u rot\/\/Herbert took board games too seriously, often appearing sullen after losing.
erudite\/\/showing or having profound knowledge\/\/em rat duoc, uyen bac, hoc rong\/\/Before the Internet, the library was typically where you would find erudite readers.
esoteric\/\/confined to and understandable by only an enlightened inner circle\/\/em sot that roi ,bi truyen\/\/Map collecting is an esoteric hobby to most, but to geography geeks it is a highly enjoyable pasttime.
fastidious\/\/overly concerned with details; fussy\/\/fussy, om som, kho tinh, ken ca chon canh\/\/Whitney is fastidious about her shoes, arranging them on a shelf in a specific order, each pair evenly spaced.
harried\/\/troubled persistently especially with petty annoyances\/\/ha ri, ha? ri`, lam phien\/\/With a team of new hires to train, martha was constantly harried with little questions and could not focus on her projects.
imprudent\/\/not wise\/\/khong phai duong, khong than trong, khinh suat\/\/Hitler, like Napoleon, made the imprudent move of invading Russia in winter, suffering even more casualities than Napoleon had.
polemic\/\/a strong verbal or written attack on someone or something\/\/bo lem me, but chien\/\/The professor launched into a polemic, claiming that Freudian theory was a pack of lies that absolutely destroyed European literary theory.
placate\/\/cause to be more favorably inclined; gain the good will of\/\/ba lua ca, xoa diu, lam cho bot gian\/\/I was able to placate the angry mob of students by promising to bring cookies on Monday.
nuance\/\/a subtle difference in meaning or opinion or attitude\/\/sac thai\/\/Because of the nuances involved in this case, I hired an outside consultant to advice us and help.
truncate\/\/reduce the length of something\/\/cat ngan, cat cut\/\/The soccer game was truncated when the monsoon rain began to fall.
economical\/\/avoiding wast, efficient\/\/kinh te\/\/Journalists favor an economical style of writing, in which no unnecessary words are used and every sentence is as short as possible.
disseminate\/\/cause to become widely known\/\/disseminate\/\/Before the effects of anaesthesia were disseminated, patients had to experience the full pain of a surgery.
antipathy\/\/an intense feeling of dislike or aversion\/\/anti bao thy, ac cam, ghet\/\/Maria had an antipathy for tour groups, often bolting to the other side of the museum as soon as she saw a chaperone leading a group of wide-eyed tourists.
sumptuous\/\/splendid and expensive-looking\/\/sam thanh, xa xi, xa hoa, long lay\/\/The banquet was a sumptuous, luxurious meal.
opulence\/\/wealth as evidenced by sumptuous living\/\/ong phu lang, su giau co\/\/Russian oligarch are famous for their opulence, living in fancy homes and dining on expensive cavier.
mundane\/\/1. repetitive and boring; not sprititual 2. Relating to the ordinary world\/\/man dem\/\/1. Nancy found doing doing dishes a thoroughly mundane task, although Peter found a kind of Zen pleasure in the chore. 2. Though we think of the pope as someone always dealing in holy matters, he is also concerned with mundane events, such as deciding when to set his alarm each morning.
